pr_review_comment_body:
This will cause us to need to construct a new function every time we want to make an API call.

To be more economical, we could try something like this:

```python
class APICallWrapper(object):
    def __init__(self, func_that_makes_an_api_call, instance=None, owner=None):
        ...
        self._instance = instance
        self._owner = owner

    def __get__(self, instance, owner):
        return self.__class__(func_that_makes_an_api_call, instance=instance, owner=owner)

    def __call__(*args, **kwargs):
        ...
```

As another idea, we can consider using https://pypi.python.org/pypi/wrapt to power the decorator, so that we don't have to think at all about the descriptor. Though that would introduce its own slowness.

If we keep this code as-is for now, we should use `@wraps` on the definition of `call`.

I have no particular opinion about this, I just saw this being done in this way in [resolwe-bio](https://github.com/genialis/resolwe-bio/tree/master/resolwe_bio/tests/files) and assumed it is the way to go.

Perhaps one argument for all files being in the same directory is that some files will be an output of a process and at the same time input for several other processes.

@mstajdohar, @jkokosar do you have any thoughts on this?

Actually, isn't the `_initialized` flag redundant, given the `_cluster` attribute?  If it was set to `None` at the class level, then you could make `__del__` as:

```python
    def __del__(self):
        if self._cluster is not None:
            self.close()
```

I think the version of node we use doesn't really support ES6 [destructuring](http://ariya.ofilabs.com/2013/02/es6-and-destructuring-assignment.html) based on this [compatibility table](http://node.green/) but we could at least do:

```js
var thing = result[0];
var other_thing = result[1];
```

with of course more meaningful names than `thing`.

